tLog()` which has the CART_UPDATED entries\n4. `await` the result - yields\n\nSo the analytics handler DOES run within the same call to emit, synchronously. The `await` at the end yields, but the handler has already modified `productCounts`.\n\nThen the question is: does `orders.createOrder` continue to return `id` before or after the handler runs? Let me trace:\n\n```js\n// orders.createOrder:\nbus.emit(Events.ORDER_CREATED, event);  // starts emit, handler runs synchronously, await yields\nreturn id;  // this runs synchronously, before await yields\n```\n\nNo wait - `bus.emit` is `async emit(...)`. When you call an async function, it runs synchronously up to the first `await`. Inside emit:\n```\nasync emit(event, payload) {\n  this.eventLog.push(...);          // sync\n  const handlers = this.handlers.get(event);  // sync\n  if (handlers) {\n    for (const handler of handlers) {\n      await handler(payload);       // FIRST AWAIT - handler runs sync, then yields\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSo `await handler(payload)` - first the handler is called (sync), then `await` wraps the result in a promise and yields. The function `emit` suspends at this point. Control returns to the caller (`orders.createOrder`), which then `return id;`.\n\nSo: the handler DOES run synchronously before `createOrder` returns! The `await` happens after the handler completes, suspending emit for the next microtask, but the handler itself has already modified `productCounts`.\n\nSo why does the test fail? Let me add some debug logging.\n\nActually, let me just re-run the test with more info:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3362,"cache_read_input_tokens":39200,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3362},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"27ae9e91-eaa1-486f-81ac-6cc3839834ee","uuid":"69b336